The order matters. If you put them like this:

    Route::get(&#39;/{product_slug}&#39;, &#39;HomeController@subpage&#39;);
    // ...
    Route::get(&#39;/signup&#39;, &#39;AuthController@signup&#39;);
    // ...

It will evaluate the `/{product_slug}` route first. This means, you&#39;ll need to add logic to know if the request wants to go to the `signup`route.

If you do this instead:

    Route::get(&#39;/signup&#39;, &#39;AuthController@signup&#39;);
    // ...
    Route::get(&#39;/{product_slug}&#39;, &#39;HomeController@subpage&#39;);
    // ...

Your app will evaluate the `/signup` first and then go to the `/{product_slug}`. So there&#39;s no need to add extra validation. You&#39;ll need to just validate your business logic: if the slug belongs to a product.

    public function subpage(Request $request)
    {
        Product::whereSlug($request-&gt;get(&#39;product_slug&#39;))-&gt;firstOrFail();
        // ...
    }

-----

As a side note, I suggest you to add a route differentiator to your endpoint, to avoid this kind of situations:

    Route::get(&#39;/slug/{product_slug}&#39;, &#39;HomeController@subpage&#39;);
    //          ^^^^^^

